Current debates center on transparency versus control. Open-source AI models allow the research community to audit weights, training data, and inference code, fostering transparency and peer review. Closed-source systems give organisations tighter control over misuse but reduce external accountability and peer review. Regulatory frameworks reflect these tensions: the EU AI Act applies lighter obligations to open-source foundation models, while the US Executive Order on AI requires dual-use foundation model developers to share safety test results with the government, and frontier companies have made voluntary safety commitments. Trade‑offs include: open source enables broader scrutiny and collaborative safety improvements but may facilitate misuse if safeguards are weak; closed source limits misuse through centralized control but hinders independent verification and can create accountability gaps. For long‑term AI safety, a hybrid approach—open weights paired with restricted fine‑tuning APIs—is emerging as a practical middle ground, combining transparency for auditing with controlled deployment to mitigate misuse.
