CallToolResult(content=[TextContent(type='text', text='{\n  "critique": "Critic unavailable: \'SamplingResult\' object has no attribute \'content\'",\n  "corrected_answer": "Governments should consider regulating large language models (LLMs) to balance innovation with public safety. Regulation can enhance safety by requiring safety testing, transparency, and accountability, as seen in the EU AI Act which classifies high-capability general\\u2011purpose AI models above 10^25 FLOPs as high\\u2011risk and imposes systemic risk obligations, and the US Executive Order on AI (Oct 2023) that mandates dual\\u2011use foundation model developers to share safety test results with the government. Such measures help prevent misuse, enable external audit, and promote alignment techniques like Constitutional AI that reduce reliance on human labellers.\\n\\nHowever, regulation also poses trade\\u2011offs that could impede innovation. Overly stringent rules may increase compliance costs, slow model development, and discourage open\\u2011source collaboration. Open\\u2011source LLMs foster transparency and allow the research community to audit weights, training data, and inference code, but closed\\u2011source systems, while offering tighter control over misuse, reduce external accountability and peer review. The EU AI Act applies lighter obligations to open\\u2011source foundation models, recognizing their distinct risk profile.\\n\\nThus, effective regulation should be proportionate: targeting high\\u2011capability models with clear safety obligations while preserving space for open\\u2011source innovation and avoiding blanket bans that could stifle technological progress. Policymakers must weigh the benefits of reduced harm and increased public trust against the risks of hindering competitive advancement and limiting the societal benefits that LLMs can deliver.",\n  "is_sufficient": true\n}', annotations=None, meta=None)], structured_content={'result': '{\n  "critique": "Critic una