esting, auditability, and responsible release practices\\u2014appears most effective.\\" This is a recommendation not in results. Not supported. Could be considered hallucination (since not in results). Also \\"mandated safety testing\\" is somewhat implied by US Executive Order requiring safety test sharing, but not exactly mandated safety testing for all. \\"auditability\\" is implied for open-source. \\"responsible release practices\\" not in results. So likely hallucination.\\n\\n- \\"Therefore, rather than choosing one extreme, policies should encourage open-source models with robust safety oversight and require closed-source developers to submit to independent verification, balancing innovation with risk mitigation.\\" This is also not in results. So hallucination.\\n\\nNow contradictions: any claim that conflicts with search results.\\n\\nCheck: The draft says \\"EU AI Act apply lighter obligations to open-source foundation models\\". That\'s consistent. \\"US Executive Order mandates safety test sharing for dual-use models\\" consistent. No contradictions.\\n\\nOmissions: important points in results the draft missed.\\n\\nImportant points from search results:\\n\\n- The EU AI Act classifies general-purpose AI models above 10^25 FLOPs as high-capability and subjects them to systemic risk obligations. (From Section \'Government Approaches\' in LLM Regulation). Draft didn\'t mention this classification or systemic risk obligations.\\n\\n- The US Executive Order on AI (Oct 2023) requires dual-use foundation model developers to share safety test results with the government. (Mentioned, yes.)\\n\\n- Frontier AI companies including Anthropic, Google DeepMind, and OpenAI signed voluntary safety commitments at the UK AI Safety Summit (2023). Draft mentioned industry voluntary commitments exist but didn\'t name the companies or summit. Could be considered omission of specific detail.\\n\\n- Constitutional AI (CAI) uses a set of principles to guide self-critique and re