Recent breakthroughs in quantum computing include Google's Willow chip (2024) achieving below-threshold error correction, a key step toward fault-tolerant quantum computing; IBM's Condor processor with over 1000 qubits, the largest superconducting quantum processor publicly demonstrated; and Microsoft's announcement of topological qubits in 2025, which claim inherently lower error rates than traditional transmon architectures. Practically, quantum advantage for optimization problems relevant to logistics and drug discovery is anticipated within the next 5–10 years. Additionally, post-quantum cryptography standards (NIST PQC) are being finalised to safeguard classical infrastructure against future quantum attacks. A hybrid approach - open weights with restricted fine-tuning APIs - is emerging as a practical middle ground for safety-conscious deployment.
