The search results highlight three key points in the open‑source versus closed‑source debate. First, open‑source AI models promote transparency and enable the research community to audit weights, training data, and inference code. Second, closed‑source systems give organisations tighter control over misuse, but this comes at the cost of reduced external accountability and limited peer review. Third, the EU AI Act differentiates between open‑source foundation models and closed proprietary models, imposing lighter obligations on the former. These points capture the main trade‑offs: openness supports scrutiny and accountability, while proprietary control can limit misuse but hinders independent verification. The search results do not provide evidence about how these trade‑offs affect long‑term AI safety, nor do they support claims about malicious actor access, proliferation speed, regulatory loopholes, resource asymmetries, or specific hybrid policies. Consequently, based solely on the supplied information, it is not possible to recommend one approach as superior for long‑term AI safety.
